SIMPLE: gorge
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gorge
<hw>Gorge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>gorge</ets>,
LL. <ets>gorgia</ets>, throat, narrow pass, and <ets>gorga</ets> abyss,
whirlpool, prob. fr. L. <ets>gurgea</ets> whirlpool, gulf, abyss; cf.
Skr. <ets>gargara</ets> whirlpool, <ets>g⟦rsdot⟧</ets> to devour. Cf.
<er>Gorget</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The throat; the gullet; the
canal by which food passes to the stomach.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wherewith he gripped her <qex>gorge</qex> with so great pain.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now, how abhorred! . . . my <qex>gorge</qex> rises at it.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A narrow passage or entrance</def>; as: <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>A defile between mountains.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The entrance
into a bastion or other outwork of a fort; -- usually synonymous with
<xex>rear</xex>. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Bastion</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is gorged or swallowed, especially by a
hawk or other fowl.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And all the way, most like a brutish beast,⟦br⟧
e spewed up his <qex>gorge</qex>, that all did him detest.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A filling or choking of a passage or channel by an
obstruction; <as>as, an ice <ex>gorge</ex> in a river</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A concave molding; a
cavetto.</def> <rj><au>Gwilt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The groove of a pulley.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Angling)</fld> <def>A primitive device used instead
of a fishhook, consisting of an object easy to be swallowed but
difficult to be ejected or loosened, as a piece of bone or stone pointed
at each end and attached in the middle to a line.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Gorge circle</b></col> <fld>(Gearing)</fld>, <cd>the
outline of the smallest cross section of a hyperboloid of
revolution.</cd> -- <col><b>Circle of the gorge</b></col>
<fld>(Math.)</fld>, <cd>a minimum circle on a surface of revolution, cut
out by a plane perpendicular to the axis.</cd> -- <col><b>Gorge
fishing</b></col>, <cd>trolling with a dead bait on a double hook which
the fish is given time to swallow, or gorge.</cd> -- <col><b>Gorge
hook</b></col>, <cd>two fishhooks, separated by a piece of lead.</cd>
<au>Knight.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gorge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gorge
<hw>Gorge</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Gorged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Gorging</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>gorger</ets>. See <er>Gorge</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To swallow; especially, to swallow with greediness, or in large
mouthfuls or quantities.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fish has <qex>gorged</qex> the hook.</q>
<rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To glut; to fill up to the throat; to
satiate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The giant <qex>gorged</qex> with flesh.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Gorge</qex> with my blood thy barbarous appetite.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gorge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Gorge
<hw>Gorge</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To eat greedily and to
satiety.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gorged</ent>⟦br⟧
